After a 4-month follow-up, the nonstimulated serum Tg level decreased from 143 to 0.109 ng/ml. After 1 day of administration of 185 MBq (5 mCi) of I-131, excepting for the physiological retention of stomach (black arrows) and bladder (red arrow), no radioactive uptake was observed in the neck and pelvic cavity on the diagnostic I-131-WBS (
Figure 2
). So further SPECT/CT fused imaging was not performed. Up to now, the patient was regularly reexamined for thyroid hormone and Tg level, as well as cervical ultrasound. No abnormal tissue and significant lymph node were observed on the cervical ultrasound images. The Tg level was stable between 0.1 and 0.5 ng/ml after twice L-T4 withdrawal.
